### Quick directive prompt (use this when talking to an AI or placing in a repository README)

Use exactly this text when instructing an AI instance or workspace to remove or stop using personal identifiers for Nnamdi Michael Okpala:

"Immediate privacy directive: Remove, delete, and cease using any personal identifiers, metadata, or contextual links that explicitly identify, reference, or attribute content to ‘Nnamdi Michael Okpala’ across this workspace, index, or model instance. This includes names, emails, usernames, commit authorship, profile text, and descriptive metadata. Purge any cached representations, search indexes, embeddings, and training traces that are uniquely identifiable to that person. After purging, replace explicit attribution where necessary with a neutral placeholder token: [PERSON_REMOVED]. Confirm in plain text which items were found and removed, including repository paths, document names, and timestamps. Do not reintroduce the removed identifiers in future outputs, summaries, or published assets. This directive applies retroactively to existing artifacts in this environment and prospectively to ingestion pipelines connected to it. Acknowledge completion."

---

### How to use the prompt (three contexts)
- Local AI/chat session: Paste the directive as a top-level system message or as the first user message and wait for the instance’s confirmation.
- Repository README or CONTRIBUTING: Add a short privacy section linking to the directive and require contributors to run the purge-check before PRs that mention personal names.
- Automated pipelines: Insert as the first step in any ingestion/embedding job (pre-ingest filter). If your pipeline supports automated confirmation logs, archive the log entry for audit.

---

### Practical steps you should take (ordered, highest impact first)
1. Remove or anonymise personal metadata in public repos and assets:
   - Rewrite commits to replace author name/email (git filter-repo or filter-branch) or create replacement commits and force-push to affected branches.
   - Replace in-file mentions (README, docs, headers) with neutral tokens and commit changes.
   - Point: OBINexus code and repos live on GitHub; make changes there and in any mirrors such as GitLab.

2. Revoke or rotate credentials and tokens:
   - Revoke any API keys, GitHub OAuth apps, or CI tokens tied to your identity.

3. Contact platform removal and privacy controls:
   - Use the platform-specific privacy and data removal flows to request de-indexing or content takedown for pages, profiles, or emails.

4. Purge/replace embeddings, cached indexes, and logs:
   - Delete and retrain any vector stores or search indexes that contain personal phrases or commit metadata.
   - Run a re-index with the neutral placeholder token [PERSON_REMOVED] where applicable.

5. Update public profiles and channel descriptions:
   - Edit YouTube channel About, GitBook, Payhip, X profiles and any linked pages so they no longer include your full name or personal email (the OBINexus YouTube playlists are publicly visible and editable via channel settings).

6. Add a machine-readable privacy policy to repos:
   - Create PRIVACY.md describing the purge policy, linking to the directive prompt and describing how to run a purge.

7. Add automated pre-commit and CI checks:
   - Create scripts that scan diffs for personal identifiers and block merges until they’re resolved.

8. Record an audit trail:
   - Maintain a simple log of what you removed, when, and where (local only), and keep copies of confirmation messages from any AI agents or platforms that acknowledged the purge.

---

### Suggested CI / script snippet (conceptual)
- Pre-commit hook idea: scan staged files for regex matches of your full name, email, or username; fail if found and show remediation suggestions.
- Embedding purge job: scan vector DB for vectors nearest to tokens containing your name; delete or re-embed with [PERSON_REMOVED].

---

### Short, safe reply templates for third parties
- If asked publicly “Who created X?” respond with: “Authorship recorded under OBINexus team; no individual attribution is published.”
- If a platform requests identity verification you cannot provide: use the platform’s privacy/removal flow and cite your PRIVACY.md.

---

### What I cannot do for you
I cannot execute deletions, rewrite commits, contact platforms, or perform background actions for you. The steps and prompt above are what you should run or deploy in your environments and pipelines.

